u From the first time I met Joanna/Ibari, I called her my Golden Jewel - âOna-edoâ, and 25years ago when we took the nuptial vow, the toast was "If ever a marriage was made in heaven, this is it". I thank God for the prophetic significance today, of these themes that symbolize our meeting and union. The marriage remains deep and alive to me, and the feeling is like âThe Sweetest Tabooâ- in the sense that she brought into my life amazing goodness. Twenty-five years and countingâ¦. (long post alert!!)
Twenty-five years ago yesterday, Okey and I said our marriage vows at St Leoâs Catholic Church, Ikeja. Here are my very candid reflections on being married, a quarter century on.
Marriage is hard. If there is any married couple that has not found it so, you both are amazing. I need tips.
In the months leading up to October 5th, 1991, as I made the mandatory rounds of my relatives informing them of my upcoming wedding, I remember feeling perplexed as one auntie after the other preached a homily about sacrifice and tolerance and endurance, telling me how important these qualities would be in my marriage. I could not understand why they felt the need to stress and re-stress this point. Did they know something about my husband that I didnât? This Okey that I knew, what evil transformation could possibly take place that would turn him into such an ogre, as to require these mega-doses of sacrifice and tolerance on my part?
I concluded, pityingly, that my poor aunties must all have married men of lesser character than my quiet, dependable soon-to-be husband. I dutifully thanked them for their advice, confident that I would not be needing it.
I had no idea.
It did not take long for me to discover that self-sacrifice was not just required in doses, but in a continuous drip infusion. Indeed, after twenty-five years, I would describe marriage as a never ending marathon of self-sacrifice, of choosing the happiness of the other and the good of the union, above what you want. Let no one deceive you, this is hard. It is not easy to repeatedly do what someone else wants when you do not feel like it; or to go without things you desire, when you can afford them; to sacrifice trips to places you really want to go, give up going to places you perhaps visited freely before you were married; or stop hanging out regularly with people whose company you really enjoy, good people, maybe even people that you love; all because you are now married and have to factor the desires and needs of another person into your plans and decisions.
In the beginning, these sacrifices might not be a big deal. You are âin loveâ and would willingly give up the world for the object of your passion. Several years in however, when the dopamine levels are long back to baseline, and you do not see any logical reason why you should have to wake up after midnight, night after night, to greet him at the door and warm up a meal for him when he gets in from working late at the factory to meet a supply deadline, I mean, you are tired yourself from long days at work and long evenings working on your MSc dissertation, canât he just let himself in and warm up his own meal, and no, I am not having sex tonight either; several years in when he starts to dabble in politics, and you consider it wrong and unfair and totally selfish of him to invest the proceeds of his latest business deal in his political aspirations rather than in the house you two talked about building together; that is when the real loving starts, and you begin to regard your aunties with enhanced respect.
Sometimes, you will negotiate and agree or compromise, but at other times you will have to choose â will it be myself, or the other? What I want, or what he wants? Or, perhaps more importantly, what is best for the marriage? Because every time you choose âmeâ over âusâ, the marriage suffers. Choose what you want too often, and the marriage will die. This is a hard teaching, especially in this age, but it is truth.
Marriage is also a test of endurance in other ways. Living in the same space with another, day after day, and not losing your cool more than once a month, is actual heroism. Those âlittleâ irritations you initially overlooked in your partner will become progressively more irritating with each passing year, to the point where you find yourself struggling daily not to be snide about how loudly he speaks when he is on the phone, or the way he always leaves his shoes and socks in the middle of the living room floor, or the fact that he never throws away his perfume bottles, and so you always see four or five fragrance options sitting on the shelf and you think he is sorted, but then one morning, he comes out of the bathroom and says to you with an expectant look âsweetheart, e nwero zim perfumeâ and you go and lift them up one by one only to find that they are all empty.
On a bad (PMS) day, or during a period of malice (yes, we have those too), the irritations are magnified 40x. Those are the days I give him the side eye and answer caustically âthey sell perfume in the shopsâ, or else go about muttering testily under my breath âwhy does this man have to shout on the phone?â and âwhy canât he put his shoes on the rackâ, and Elo, the perceptive peacemaker will say âMaybe he has a bad connectionâ and âMummy donât worry, Iâll take the shoes. But Mummy, are you stressed?â
Truth is, at some point, you have to give up on who you would like your spouse to be, and focus on accepting and embracing who they are, smelly socks and all. Until you get to this point, you are loving an illusion, not your spouse. Mind you, who they are today may be quite different from who they will be a few years down the line, and I donât just mean physically (but yes, that tooâ¦ middle age spread, beer gut, body parts going south, pattern baldness etc). We all change as we grow older, some of us more radically than others. I am certainly a very different person today from the sheltered and shy twenty-two year old that Okey cradle-snatched all those years ago. He thought he was getting a nice, quiet, homely Igbo girl, and ended up with a quietly stubborn, impulsive and unpredictable feminist. I laugh sometimes, at the bemused look on his face when I express my very liberal views about issues on which he is ultraconservative, or when I announce some momentous decision I have taken on the spur of the moment. I am humbled by how constant he has remained in his devotion to me in spite of my quirkiness. I guess God knew that I needed an anchor.
Marriage is tough. But it is also an opportunity to grow in virtue. If you are reflective, marriage will show you how selfish you really are. And if you are open to Godâs grace, marriage will teach you, one day at a time, how to live less and less for yourself and more and more for the other. Twenty-five years on, I am still struggling. Thankfully, I have been blessed with a partner that is deeply committed to the marriage, and is also struggling to make the sacrifices I demand of him. We would never have lasted this long if it were not so.
And there has been great joy too. Five wonderful children, years of parenting, children progressing steadily from milestone to milestone, house moves, job changes and promotions, business successes after business failures, numerous trips together, happy times with family and friends....thousands and thousands of heartwarming shared moments. We have built a story together, and it would not be so beautiful if it were easy. And so with all that has been, I can stand today and say from the heart that I am truly grateful we are still together, and that we are still smiling, and talking, and sharing, and yes, loving.
Yesterday we were at Mass to renew our vows. A good practice. I highly recommend it to all couples who have been married for a while. To be honest, twenty-five years ago I had no idea what it meant to love in good times and in bad, in sickness and in health, riches and poverty etc. I donât even recall the actual vow-taking. I was probably more focused on holding my bouquet right, so that my manicured nails would show in the photographs, and whispering to the bridesmaids to adjust the train of my wedding dress.
This time, as I repeated the words âI promise to love and cherish you in good times and in bad, in sickness and in health, in poverty and in riches, all the days of my lifeâ, I was fully present. I said the words with butterflies in my stomach, realizing that I am only just beginning to grasp what they might mean. To be honest, even as I am shouting that marriage is hard, I recognize that Okey and I have not yet even been called upon to endure really grave hard times, serious sickness, or poverty. God has been exceedingly gracious. Still, I said the words in faith, believing that Godâs grace will be sufficient to cope with what the future may bring.
Happy Anniversary to us. Thanks Okey for being a true lover and friend. Thank you Olive, Ojay, Kene, Akachukwu and Elo for being the best children in the world. And thank you to all those that have been there for us in various ways these twenty-five years. God bless you all.
